The elastic file system.

This service is a managed network filesystem that many Linux instances mount at the same time, across zones, across accounts, and even from on-premises over a private link. Unlike a block volume, it's regional: data is replicated across multiple zones automatically, capacity grows and shrinks elastically, and you pay per gigabyte stored with no provisioning.

Clients reach it through mount targets, one per zone, each with a private address in your network, and security groups on the mount target control which instances can connect; all mount targets resolve to the same filesystem, so a write through any one is immediately visible to all.

It's Linux-only and standards-compliant; Windows clients need the Windows file server instead. Typical workloads are content shared across web servers, Linux home directories, shared config across a scaling group, and container volumes.
